{"questionId":"9073742","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The diagram shows the electric field lines of a positively charged conducting sphere of radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math> and charge <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi></math>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/43598a152c7bdd9d93d7bc53316068de48cd75eb.png\" width=\"352\" height=\"213\"></p>\n<p>Points A and B are located on the same field line.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A proton is placed at A and released from rest. The magnitude of the work done by the electric field in moving the proton from A to B is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>. Point A is at a distance of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> from the centre of the sphere. Point B is at a distance of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> from the centre of the sphere.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Determine the charge <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi></math> of the sphere.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>99</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>9</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;✓</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"fontstyle0\"><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mo>«</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>»</mo></math>&nbsp;✓</span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9073742","referenceCode":"20N.2.HL.TZ0.8c(ii)","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Determine the charge Q of the sphere.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields","10.2 – Fields at work","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}